{"parentUuid":null,"isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"afd7b3466a6880b47","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"You are a web research agent. Use WebSearch and WebFetch (load them via ToolSearch query \"select:WebSearch,WebFetch\" first if not available). The current date is June 2026.\n\nRESEARCH ANGLE: The autonomy threshold for self-improving code agents — what success rate is needed for a self-improvement loop to be net-positive (more good commits than regressions), and when/why such loops stall or collapse with weak base models.\n\nResearch concretely:\n- Self-improving AI / self-improving coding agents research: STOP (Self-Taught Optimizer), Gödel Machine / \"Darwin Gödel Machine\" (Sakana AI 2025), SICA (Self-Improving Coding Agent), RSI (recursive self-improvement) empirical results.\n- Any analysis of the success-rate / capability threshold below which a self-improvement loop produces net regressions (compounding errors, error accumulation, model collapse in self-training loops).\n- Evidence that weak base models cannot bootstrap self-improvement (the generator is too weak to propose improvements that survive verification), vs strong models that can.\n- \"Model collapse\" from training on self-generated data — what's the failure mode.\n- Quantify if possible: what SWE-bench-ish pass rate corresponds to a loop that compounds vs collapses.\n\nRun at least 4-5 searches with varied queries. Fetch authoritative sources (arXiv papers, Sakana AI blog, METR, lab blog posts). Cross-check.\n\nReturn a list of FALSIFIABLE CLAIMS, each as: the claim, supporting detail/number, and source URL. Flag conflicts. Do NOT write files. Return findings only as your final message."},"uuid":"7f8cc05b-82e8-44a0-be18-bd752d209a0c","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:34:26.888Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
