{"parentUuid":"6a062e03-a990-4f8d-8990-d0b1d2097c41","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"afd7b3466a6880b47","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01TzC1DNRHjxKXtnnGQahBds","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01SHFQVy6oCr4zjWgzGpfjad","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2412.02674","prompt":"Extract the core findings about the \"generation-verification gap\" and self-improvement capability of LLMs. Specifically: how does self-improvement ability scale with model capability/size? Is there evidence that weaker models cannot self-improve while stronger ones can? Any quantitative threshold or metric (the \"generation-verification gap\" definition and how it scales with pretraining flops/model size). What happens to weak models in the loop?"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3040,"cache_read_input_tokens":18220,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3040,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG25DWKXTTSNvAoew12j","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"fd76a958-710a-4e02-8888-cbdd933c4590","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:07.995Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"fd76a958-710a-4e02-8888-cbdd933c4590","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"afd7b3466a6880b47","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01TzC1DNRHjxKXtnnGQahBds","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_014g6L6ontziJbtbtj5YU599","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2504.15228v2","prompt":"Extract specific numbers and claims: starting and ending SWE-bench Verified scores, what base models were used, and crucially any statement about WEAK models degrading self-improvement or failing to self-improve. Did they observe self-improvement stall or collapse with weaker models? Any mention of a stronger model needed to build scaffold for a weaker one. Any failure modes like the agent failing to propose surviving improvements."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3040,"cache_read_input_tokens":18220,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3040,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG25DWKXTTSNvAoew12j","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"20643af0-fdd4-41c0-a497-f041b74be409","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:09.714Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"20643af0-fdd4-41c0-a497-f041b74be409","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"afd7b3466a6880b47","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01TzC1DNRHjxKXtnnGQahBds","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01JR4QKHWNTKZdZzr1EjSgfL","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"\"generation-verification gap\" scales model size self-improvement larger models improve more"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3040,"cache_read_input_tokens":18220,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3040,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG25DWKXTTSNvAoew12j","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"8d3e411a-c24b-416d-8d4f-eae935372ca4","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:10.217Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"fd76a958-710a-4e02-8888-cbdd933c4590","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"afd7b3466a6880b47","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01SHFQVy6oCr4zjWgzGpfjad","type":"tool_result","content":"# Generation-Verification Gap and LLM Self-Improvement\n\nBased on the PDF content, here are the core findings:\n\n## Definition and Scaling\n\nThe **generation-verification gap** refers to the disparity between a model's ability to generate solutions versus verify their correctness. The research demonstrates this gap scales with model capability—stronger models show larger gaps between what they can generate versus what they can verify.\n\n## Scaling with Model Size\n\nThe evidence indicates a critical threshold effect:\n\n> \"weaker models cannot effectively self-improve while stronger models demonstrate measurable self-improvement capability\"\n\nThis scaling appears correlated with pretraining compute (FLOPs) and model size. The visualizations in the document (scale_relgap plots) suggest the gap widens as model capacity increases, creating asymmetric self-improvement potential.\n\n## Weak Models in the Loop\n\nWeaker models faced significant challenges:\n\n- They struggle to verify their own generations, limiting feedback quality\n- Self-correction loops provide minimal benefit since verification accuracy remains low\n- The feedback signal becomes unreliable, preventing meaningful improvement\n\n## Key Insight\n\nThe research establishes that **self-improvement isn't uniformly accessible across model scales**. Beyond a certain capability threshold, models gain sufficient verification competence to enable meaningful self-correction. Below this threshold, weak models remain trapped in a low-quality feedback loop despite theoretical access to self-improvement mechanisms.\n\nThis suggests self-improvement capability emerges as a phase transition tied to underlying model competence rather than incrementally across all scales.\n\n[Binary content (application/pdf, 3.3MB) also saved to /Users/gg/.claude/projects/-Users-gg-Work-Yogi/d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f/tool-results/webfetch-1782027308670-6rh3ms.pdf]"}]},"uuid":"eda6cc68-d0fc-4481-91ca-4e4c63637c3b","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:14.244Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":3429637,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Generation-Verification Gap and LLM Self-Improvement\n\nBased on the PDF content, here are the core findings:\n\n## Definition and Scaling\n\nThe **generation-verification gap** refers to the disparity between a model's ability to generate solutions versus verify their correctness. The research demonstrates this gap scales with model capability—stronger models show larger gaps between what they can generate versus what they can verify.\n\n## Scaling with Model Size\n\nThe evidence indicates a critical threshold effect:\n\n> \"weaker models cannot effectively self-improve while stronger models demonstrate measurable self-improvement capability\"\n\nThis scaling appears correlated with pretraining compute (FLOPs) and model size. The visualizations in the document (scale_relgap plots) suggest the gap widens as model capacity increases, creating asymmetric self-improvement potential.\n\n## Weak Models in the Loop\n\nWeaker models faced significant challenges:\n\n- They struggle to verify their own generations, limiting feedback quality\n- Self-correction loops provide minimal benefit since verification accuracy remains low\n- The feedback signal becomes unreliable, preventing meaningful improvement\n\n## Key Insight\n\nThe research establishes that **self-improvement isn't uniformly accessible across model scales**. Beyond a certain capability threshold, models gain sufficient verification competence to enable meaningful self-correction. Below this threshold, weak models remain trapped in a low-quality feedback loop despite theoretical access to self-improvement mechanisms.\n\nThis suggests self-improvement capability emerges as a phase transition tied to underlying model competence rather than incrementally across all scales.\n\n[Binary content (application/pdf, 3.3MB) also saved to /Users/gg/.claude/projects/-Users-gg-Work-Yogi/d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f/tool-results/webfetch-1782027308670-6rh3ms.pdf]","durationMs":5794,"url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2412.02674"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"fd76a958-710a-4e02-8888-cbdd933c4590","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"20643af0-fdd4-41c0-a497-f041b74be409","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"afd7b3466a6880b47","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014g6L6ontziJbtbtj5YU599","type":"tool_result","content":"# Self-Improving Coding Agent: Key Findings\n\n## SWE-Bench Verified Performance\n- **Starting score**: 17% (iteration 0)\n- **Ending score**: 53% (iteration 14)\n- Performance gains ranged from \"17% to 53% on a random subset of SWE Bench Verified\"\n\n## Base Models Used\nThe system employed Claude 3.5 Sonnet (v2) for most agents, with o3-mini for the reasoning agent. The authors noted: \"the meta-improvement task is a complicated long-horizon task which requires powerful models.\"\n\n## Weak Model Degradation\nThe paper presents critical evidence of performance collapse with weaker reasoning models. On AIME 2024 and GPQA Diamond tasks, when o3-mini (a strong reasoning model) was available, the agent showed minimal improvement. The authors observed that \"crude components aiming to induce reasoning behaviour...may in fact interrupt the reasoning chain of thought of a reasoning model.\"\n\nThey concluded: \"For 'reasoning models' such as o1, o3-mini or DeepSeek's R1, we suspect...the inclusion of crude components...may in fact interrupt...resulting in a drop in performance.\"\n\n## Failure Modes Identified\nA significant limitation was acknowledged: \"One key difficulty was getting the LLM-based agent to autonomously come up with truely novel, innovative, feasible and interesting modification ideas at each meta-improvement step.\" Path dependency problems emerged where \"poor quality initial feature suggestions...often lowering the quality of subsequent feature suggestions.\""}]},"uuid":"1317b751-57cc-4930-8e65-d23f84c5599b","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:16.653Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":254615,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Self-Improving Coding Agent: Key Findings\n\n## SWE-Bench Verified Performance\n- **Starting score**: 17% (iteration 0)\n- **Ending score**: 53% (iteration 14)\n- Performance gains ranged from \"17% to 53% on a random subset of SWE Bench Verified\"\n\n## Base Models Used\nThe system employed Claude 3.5 Sonnet (v2) for most agents, with o3-mini for the reasoning agent. The authors noted: \"the meta-improvement task is a complicated long-horizon task which requires powerful models.\"\n\n## Weak Model Degradation\nThe paper presents critical evidence of performance collapse with weaker reasoning models. On AIME 2024 and GPQA Diamond tasks, when o3-mini (a strong reasoning model) was available, the agent showed minimal improvement. The authors observed that \"crude components aiming to induce reasoning behaviour...may in fact interrupt the reasoning chain of thought of a reasoning model.\"\n\nThey concluded: \"For 'reasoning models' such as o1, o3-mini or DeepSeek's R1, we suspect...the inclusion of crude components...may in fact interrupt...resulting in a drop in performance.\"\n\n## Failure Modes Identified\nA significant limitation was acknowledged: \"One key difficulty was getting the LLM-based agent to autonomously come up with truely novel, innovative, feasible and interesting modification ideas at each meta-improvement step.\" Path dependency problems emerged where \"poor quality initial feature suggestions...often lowering the quality of subsequent feature suggestions.\"","durationMs":6702,"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2504.15228v2"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"20643af0-fdd4-41c0-a497-f041b74be409","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"8d3e411a-c24b-416d-8d4f-eae935372ca4","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"afd7b3466a6880b47","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01JR4QKHWNTKZdZzr1EjSgfL","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"\"generation-verification gap\" scales model size self-improvement larger models improve more\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"[Literature Review] Mind the Gap: Examining the Self-Improvement Capabilities of Large Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://www.themoonlight.io/en/review/mind-the-gap-examining-the-self-improvement-capabilities-of-large-language-models\"},{\"title\":\"[2412.02674] Mind the Gap: Examining the Self-Improvement Capabilities of Large Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2412.02674\"},{\"title\":\"Mind the Gap: Examining the Self-Improvement Capabilities of\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2412.02674\"},{\"title\":\"Mind the Gap: Examining the Self-Improvement Capabilities of Large Language Models | OpenReview\",\"url\":\"https://openreview.net/forum?id=mtJSMcF3ek\"},{\"title\":\"MIND THE GAP: EXAMINING THE SELF-IMPROVEMENT ...\",\"url\":\"https://proceedings.iclr.cc/paper_files/paper/2025/file/63943ee9fe347f3d95892cf87d9a42e6-Paper-Conference.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Mind the Gap: Examining the Self-Improvement Capabilities of Large Language Models | Carson Eisenach\",\"url\":\"https://carson.eisenach.org/publication/mind-the-gap/\"},{\"title\":\"Enhancing AI through Self-Verification | Digital Data Design Institute at Harvard\",\"url\":\"https://d3.harvard.edu/enhancing-ai-through-self-verification/\"},{\"title\":\"Mind the Gap: Examining the Self-Improvement Capabilities of Large Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/386419076_Mind_the_Gap_Examining_the_Self-Improvement_Capabilities_of_Large_Language_Models\"},{\"title\":\"Mind the Gap: Examining the Self-Improvement\",\"url\":\"https://openreview.net/pdf?id=Hgv0tqgaiA\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about the generation-verification gap and its relationship to model size:\n\n## Key Findings\n\nThe generation-verification gap (GV-Gap) is a mathematical quantity that governs self-improvement in LLMs, and a variant of this gap scales monotonically with the model pre-training flops.\n\nLarger models demonstrate a more pronounced GV-Gap, which suggests that the efficacy of self-improvement correlates with model size.\n\n## What the Generation-Verification Gap Measures\n\nThe GV-Gap captures the 'precision' of the model's verification over its own generations and measures the model's ability to accurately verify its own outputs, providing a clear indicator of its potential for self-enhancement.\n\n## Task-Dependent Performance\n\nThe relationship between model size and self-improvement is not uniform across all tasks. Models struggled to self-improve on factual tasks where the complexity of verification is similar to that of generation, but in tasks like solving Sudoku puzzles where verification is computationally simpler than generation, significant improvements were observed in the largest models.\n\nDifferent verification methods impact this scaling behavior differently, pointing to the necessity for model selection in self-improvement strategies.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"f59442bf-77dd-485a-978c-eb414f4bde36","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:24.982Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"\"generation-verification gap\" scales model size self-improvement larger models improve more","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_019kjtyJjFT8RjZEMZMPN3WY","content":[{"title":"[Literature Review] Mind the Gap: Examining the Self-Improvement Capabilities of Large Language Models","url":"https://www.themoonlight.io/en/review/mind-the-gap-examining-the-self-improvement-capabilities-of-large-language-models"},{"title":"[2412.02674] Mind the Gap: Examining the Self-Improvement Capabilities of Large Language Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2412.02674"},{"title":"Mind the Gap: Examining the Self-Improvement Capabilities of","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2412.02674"},{"title":"Mind the Gap: Examining the Self-Improvement Capabilities of Large Language Models | OpenReview","url":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=mtJSMcF3ek"},{"title":"MIND THE GAP: EXAMINING THE SELF-IMPROVEMENT ...","url":"https://proceedings.iclr.cc/paper_files/paper/2025/file/63943ee9fe347f3d95892cf87d9a42e6-Paper-Conference.pdf"},{"title":"Mind the Gap: Examining the Self-Improvement Capabilities of Large Language Models | Carson Eisenach","url":"https://carson.eisenach.org/publication/mind-the-gap/"},{"title":"Enhancing AI through Self-Verification | Digital Data Design Institute at Harvard","url":"https://d3.harvard.edu/enhancing-ai-through-self-verification/"},{"title":"Mind the Gap: Examining the Self-Improvement Capabilities of Large Language Models","url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/386419076_Mind_the_Gap_Examining_the_Self-Improvement_Capabilities_of_Large_Language_Models"},{"title":"Mind the Gap: Examining the Self-Improvement","url":"https://openreview.net/pdf?id=Hgv0tqgaiA"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about the generation-verification gap and its relationship to model size:\n\n## Key Findings\n\nThe generation-verification gap (GV-Gap) is a mathematical quantity that governs self-improvement in LLMs, and a variant of this gap scales monotonically with the model pre-training flops.\n\nLarger models demonstrate a more pronounced GV-Gap, which suggests that the efficacy of self-improvement correlates with model size.\n\n## What the Generation-Verification Gap Measures\n\nThe GV-Gap captures the 'precision' of the model's verification over its own generations and measures the model's ability to accurately verify its own outputs, providing a clear indicator of its potential for self-enhancement.\n\n## Task-Dependent Performance\n\nThe relationship between model size and self-improvement is not uniform across all tasks. Models struggled to self-improve on factual tasks where the complexity of verification is similar to that of generation, but in tasks like solving Sudoku puzzles where verification is computationally simpler than generation, significant improvements were observed in the largest models.\n\nDifferent verification methods impact this scaling behavior differently, pointing to the necessity for model selection in self-improvement strategies."],"durationSeconds":14.27851166700013,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"8d3e411a-c24b-416d-8d4f-eae935372ca4","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
